<DOC><DOCNO> AP880525-0299 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-25-88 2349EDT</FILEID><FIRST>u i AM-Honduras-Attack     05-25 0217</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Honduras-Attack,0226</SECOND><HEAD>Salvadoran Guerrillas Clash With Honduran Soldiers</HEAD><DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Honduran soldiers battled leftistSalvadoran guerrillas near the border between the two countries,leaving 17 rebels dead and three soldiers seriously wounded,military sources said Wednesday.   The sources, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said thefighting occurred early Tuesday on the outskirts of Marcala, about90 miles northwest of the Honduran capital of Tegucigalpa and 40miles from the Salvadoran border.   Since the incident, Honduran air force helicopters have flownover the area to discourage further fighting, the sources said.   No further details were available.   On Saturday, the armed forces said there were intelligencereports that guerrillas of the Farabundo Marti National LiberationFront were planning to carry out terrorist actions in an effort todestabilize Honduras, a strong U.S. ally in Central America.   The front, made up of five guerrilla armies, has been fightingthe U.S.-supported government in El Salvador for more than eightyears.   The armed forces said a rebel unit entered Honduras late lastweek to try to take advantage of anti-American sentiment stirred bythe arrest and deportation to the United States of Juan RamonMatta, a suspected drug trafficker.   The Honduran Constitution forbids the extradition of Hondurancitizens.   In early April, demonstrators burned the U.S. Consulate inTegucigalpa.</TEXT></DOC>